  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">This preprint presents a structural model of the 2019-novel coronavirus spike protein, revealing a unique proteolytically-sensitive activation loop that distinguishes it from SARS-CoV and related coronaviruses. It has been cited six times, indicating a solid academic interest in its findings.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">In the rapidly evolving field of coronavirus research, this preprint plays a critical role by providing a detailed structural model of the spike protein of the 2019-novel coronavirus (nCoV). The authors, affiliated with prestigious institutions such as Cornell University and Universit\u00e9 Paris-Saclay, present findings that demonstrate a distinct proteolytically-sensitive activation loop, setting the nCoV apart from SARS-CoV and other SARS-like coronaviruses. This important distinction contributes to understanding how these viruses function and evolve, a necessity amid ongoing global health challenges.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Although this preprint has not received any funding support, its significance is underscored by the geographical and institutional diversity of the authorship, which includes experts from multiple renowned research institutions. This collaborative effort is reflected in the breadth of citation activity across various international platforms, including Future Virology and Bioinformatics and Biology Insights. Specifically, the work has garnered a total of six citations, with reviews and original research articles both acknowledging its relevance.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The social relevance of this preprint is notable, as it is indicative of the immediate engagement it generated within the scientific community. Its subsequent publication in a peer-reviewed journal further validates the quality and impact of the research, solidifying its contribution to the ongoing discourse about coronavirus dynamics. This pathway from preprint to formal publication illustrates the authors' commitment to open science and timely sharing of critical research, which is essential in addressing urgent global health threats.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Moreover, the work has been utilized in a downstream capacity, indicated by its proven reuse in seven subsequent research efforts. This underscores the tangible impact of the findings on advancing coronaviruses' structural biology and possibly informing future therapeutic strategies. While this preprint has not yet become a part of public discussion forums such as Reddit or Wikipedia, its scientific merit continues to fuel ongoing inquiry within the research community.</p>",
